-- Budimex, Orlen, Telefonica O2 May Move: Central European Equity Preview
-- Monika Rozlal
-- 2010-07-29T03:59:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-29/budimex-orlen-telefonica-o2-may-move-central-european-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in central European
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names.
Share prices are from the last close.  
 Poland’s  WIG20 Index  fell 0.5 percent, the Czech  PX Index 
dropped 0.5 percent and Hungary’s  BUX Index  slid 0.7 percent.  
 Budimex SA  (BDX PW): Poland’s second-largest builder will
publish selected first-half earnings. Budimex shares were
unchanged at 90.6 zloty.  
 Central European Media Enterprises Ltd.  (CETV CP): The east
European broadcaster that sold a stake to Time Warner Inc. cut
full-year profit and sales forecasts on a likely drop in TV
advertising spending and currency swings. Revenue for 2010 is
now likely to be as much as $725 million, from earlier
expectations of as much as $820 million. CME fell 5.6 percent to
411.7 koruna.  
 PKN Orlen SA  (PKN PW): Poland’s biggest oil refiner will
release second-quarter earnings estimates. Orlen declined 0.4
percent to 39.6 zloty.  
 Raba Nyrt.  (RABA HB): The Hungarian maker of vehicles and
auto parts said the first-half loss narrowed to 967 million
forint ($4.44 million) as domestic sales rose. The first-half
loss compares with 2.4 billion forint in the same period last
year. Sales fell 3.1 percent to 17.7 billion forint. Raba lost
1.6 percent to 861 forint.  
 Telefonica O2 Czech Republic AS  (SPTT CP): The largest
Czech phone company said second-quarter profit fell 24 percent
as customers cut spending on services and a one-off item from a
year ago wasn’t repeated. Its shares dropped 0.7 percent to 427
koruna.  
